ments in British army after World War I; and that decisions made prior to 1939 about the aviation technology to be developed for military purposes largely determined what kind of the RAF was able to fight. The chapter by Dr. G.R. Lindsay, the Chief of the Operational Research and Analysis Establishment at the Department of National Defence Headquarters in Ottawa, makes the case that, with nuclear weapons added to the scene, the impact of technology on international security has never been as great as at present, and that the competition of nations seeking the technological edge in weaponry threatens to destabilize the precarious balance that has existed since 1945.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary art and sciencexCongressesxHistoryx19th century. 0aMilitary art and sciencexCongressesxHistoryx20th century. 0aMilitary engineeringxCongressesxHistoryx19th century. 0aMilitary engineeringxCongressesxHistoryx20th century. 0aMilitary history, ModernxCongressesx19th century. 0aMilitary history, ModernxCongressesx20th century. 4aHistory. 4aHistory: Military History. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh1 aBailes, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Dominick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaycock, R. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaycock, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaycock, Ronald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLindsey, G. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcneill, William H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMessenger, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeilson, Keith,